06413nam a22009855i 9780812203547DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102010pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013940310  a(OCoLC)1037979591  a(OCoLC)1041892777  a(OCoLC)1046618617  a(OCoLC)1047030972  a(OCoLC)1049680699  a(OCoLC)1054875399  a97808122035477 a10.9783/97808122035472doi  a(DE-B1597)449178  a(OCoLC)806880912  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aGN497b.I73 2010eb 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a303.6/622200aIraq at a Distance :bWhat Anthropologists Can Teach Us About the War /ced. by Antonius C. G. M. Robben. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (200 p.) :b3 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Ethnography of Political Violence00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tEthnographic Imagination at a Distance: An Introduction to the Anthropological Study of the Iraq War -- tChapter 1. ‘‘Night Fell on a Different World’’: Dangerous Visions and the War on Terror, a Lesson from Cambodia -- tChapter 2. The War on Terror and Women’s Rights in Iraq -- tChapter 3. The War on Terror, Dismantling, and the Construction of Place: An Ethnographic Perspective from Palestine -- tChapter 4. Losing Hearts and Minds in the ‘‘War on Terrorism’’ -- tChapter 5. Mimesis in a War Among the People: What Argentina’s Dirty War Reveals About Counterinsurgency in Iraq -- tEpilogue -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Iraq War has cost innumerable lives, caused vast material destruction, and inflicted suffering on millions of people. Iraq at a Distance: What Anthropology Can Teach Us About the War focuses on the plight of the Iraqi people, caught since 2003 in the carnage between U.S. and British troops on one side and, on the other, Iraqi insurgents, militias, and foreign al Qaeda operatives.The volume is a bold attempt by six distinguished anthropologists to study a war zone too dangerous for fieldwork. They break new ground by using their ethnographic imagination as a research tool to analyze the Iraq War through insightful comparisons with previous and current armed conflicts in Cambodia, Israel, Palestine, Northern Ireland, Afghanistan, and Argentina. This innovative approach extends the book's relevance beyond a critical understanding of the devastating war in Iraq. More and more parts of the world of long-standing ethnographic interest are becoming off-limits to researchers because of the war on terror. This book serves as a model for the study of other inaccessible regions, and it shows that the impossibility of conducting ethnographic fieldwork does not condemn anthropologists to silence.Essays analyze the good-versus-evil framework of the war on terror, the deterioration of women's rights in Iraq under fundamentalist coercion, the ethnic-religious partitioning of Baghdad through the building of security walls, the excessive use of force against Iraqi civilians by U.S. counterinsurgency units, and the loss of popular support for U.S. and British forces in Iraq and Afghanistan after the brutal regimes of the Taliban and Saddam Hussein had been toppled.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIraq War, 2003-2011. 0aPolitical anthropologyvFieldworkvCase studies. 0aPolitical anthropologyxFieldworkvCase studies. 0aWar and societyvCase studies. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009. 4aFolklore. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.1 aAl-Ali, Nadje, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl-Marashi, Ibrahim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel